 public-key cryptographic algorithm became the important element of modern ciphers, since the introduction of the concept of the public cipher by Diffie and Hellman in 1976, and the development of practical public cryptographic algorithm, called RSA, in 1978. key key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2121,'641','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Unlike the private encryption, the sender and receiver use different to establish secret communication, as shown in [Figure 8]. The sender encrypts data, using the receiver\'s public and sends the result over the network The receiver decrypts the encrypted data, using the private that matches the receiver\'s public kev to restore the plain text key keys key, key','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2122,'641','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The encryption system has the advantage of establishing secure communication using the cryptographic algorithm, even though the key is not shared with other users: Each user discloses the that will be used to send data to them (called a public key), and has the key that can decrypt the information encrypted by their public (called a private key). Therefore, it has the characteristic that anyone can encrypt information, but only those who have a private corresponding to the public can decrypt the information For example, when there are \'n users in the network environment, a total of 2n keys are required across the network because each user holds two (a key and a private key) . Each user must hold public key key key key key keys public','',5,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2123,'641','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','only two keys, that is, their own private and a The public cipher has the advantage of being used for various authentication functions and secure key exchange, because only each user knows their private corresponding to the public which can be checked by everyone. RSA (Rivest, Shamir and Adleman) , ElGamal, and ECC (Elliptic Curve Cryptosystem) are the representative cryptographic algorithms key public key: key key key, public key The RSA public cryptosystem is used for encryption and authentication. The safety of this system is based on the difficulty of factoring a large integer RSA has the characteristic that ciphertext for the same message is always the same, because no random numbers are used in the encryption process. Since the safety of the RSA system depends on number p and 9, the prime number selection conditions are important key prime ElGamal was proposed in 1984 by Stanford University cryptographer, T ElGamal, and is the first public cryptographic algorithm, based on the difficulty of the discrete algebra problem: When a message is encrypted with ElGamal, its length is doubled. However, different ciphertext is created each time, even though the same message is encrypted because random numbers are used for encryption, which is a great advantage from the perspective of information security: key The Elliptic Curves encryption system is based on the discrete logarithm problem on the elliptic curve. Since its safety is high and its is fast,it draws attention a5 a new key encryption system: For example, it is known that a 1024-bit key of RSA and a 160-bit key of elliptic curve cipher have the same level of security: In addition, the ECC system is suitable for the encryption of mobile communication, such as a mobile phone with limited power supply: speed public comparison Ol tre privalte key cryptograpnic aigoriim ana pUDiic key cryptograpric aigorm <Table 4  shows the result of comparing the private encryption system and the encryption svstem, public key key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2124,'642','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 10] Hash function',NULL,'6802c9b1210c3.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b1210c3.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2125,'642','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','hash function, or a hash algorithm, is a mathematical function that outputs a short hash value (hash code) with a fixed length from random data of various sizes, as shown in Figure 10. That is, the hash function compresses an input string with a random length into a with a fixed, short length For example, HAS-160 (Hash Algorithm Standard 160), SHA-1 outputs a 160-bit result. string','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2126,'642','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The cryptographic algorithm uses keys, but the hash function does not use keys. Therefore, the same input always produces the same output. The hash function with this characteristic is used to verify the integrity that detects the error in or tampering of the message by extracting the unalterable evidence value for the input message.','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2127,'643','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 5  Basic properties of the hash function',NULL,'6802c9b12f431.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b12f431.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2128,'643','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Since the operating algorithm of the hash function is simple, it is easy to calculate h(x), when function h an input x are given, and system resources, such as a CPU and memory, are consumed relatively less. Also, th hash function should have the basic properties described in <Table 5  from the aspect of stability:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2129,'643','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The hash function is widely used in the security field because of its characteristic that the original text cannot be','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2130,'643','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','restored using the hash value. That is, the original text cannot be restored through computation using the hash value: Therefore, the hash function is mainly used to safely store sensitive data, such as the password, buta bypass attack can be made using hash collision, which outputs the same output for two different input values.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2131,'644','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','MDS(Message Digest Algorithm 5) MDS is a 128-bit hash function used for testing the integrity of the program or file. It was designated as RFC 1321 of the IETF However, it is recommended to use a safer algorithm like SHA-2 for hashing purposes because several important defects were found. MDS is frequently used for saving a password. The result of hashing a password with MDS is saved. Therefore,, a server operator or third party cannot know the original password using the hash result value of the password only stored in the system: If the user correctly inputs the password, the same hash value is returned, confirming that the password is correct SNA (secure Fiasn Aigore) MDS, which was developed from SHA, means a set of interlinked hash functions. It was first designed by the National Security Agency (NSA) in 1993,and it was designated as the national standard in the U.S. It is also called SHA-0 to distinguish the first function from the functions designed later: SHA-1, a variant of SHA-0, was announced two years later: Subsequently, four more variants were released, such as SHA-224, SHA-256, SHA-384, and SHA-512. These are called SHA-2 as a group. Currently, SHA-3, which is completely different from SHA-I and SHA-2,is under development, and it was confirmed as SHA-3 in 2012 SHA-0 and SHA-1 have a hash value of 160 bits, and SHA-224/256/384/512 provide & hash value of 224/256/384/512 bits, respectively: In addition, it is recommended to use a hash function of SHA-256 or higher for safety: On the other hand, an attack on SHA-2 has not yet been reported, but there is a possibility of an attack because SHA-2 functions use a method similar to that of SHA-1,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2132,'645','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 11] Hash function and salt',NULL,'6802c9b13b0ae.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b13b0ae.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2133,'645','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Salt is an arbitrary bit that is added when a hash function generates a hash value. Salting is to generate a hash value by adding a bit string to the original message. For example, a hash value can be created by adding salt \"topcit\" to the password   Kr5792cc\" 9C chown in [Ficuro string','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2134,'645','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','When the salting method is used, an attacker cannot check whether the password matches the salted hash','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2135,'645','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','value, even though the attacker finds the hash value of the password \" Kr5792cc\" . In addition, if different salts are used for each user, the hash values of the users who use the same password are generated differently, which significantly improves the problem of the possibility of recognition: The hash values of the salt and password can be stored in the server database, then, when the user in, the input password can be checked by hashing it: It is known that to make salt ad digest difficult to guess, all passwords should have their own salt, and the salt length should be 32 bytes or more. logs','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2136,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 6  Integrity verification method',NULL,'6802c9b14a905.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b14a905.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2137,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 12] Server file integrity check',NULL,'6802c9b15b479.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b15b479.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2138,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 13] Checking the integrity of the transmitted file',NULL,'6802c9b16b633.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b16b633.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2139,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','integrity vericalion metnoa Integrity verification methods in servers or network security, are divided into the method of detecting a error that occurs while transmitting data, and the method of preventing unauthorized modification, as shown in <Table 6  . A checksum and redundancy check (CRC) are used to test integrity when an error occurs data transmission. The checksum method, a type of duplicate test, tests integrity by adding data to obtain a checksum, converting it into a certain bit value, then adding it to the message CRC is mainly used as a method of verifying transmission data errors in the communication system, such as the Internet, A checksum is calculated at the sending side, based on polynomials that are easy to detect and corrected errors, and it is sent after adding it to the header: Then, the receiving side verifies integrity by calculating the checksum again, based on the same polynomial and comparing it with the received checksum. cyclic during','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2140,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','File integrity To ensure integrity when sending files on the Internet or posting them on website, assistant manager Kim secured a method of verifying that files are not tampered. To do so, he also sends, or posts hash values that are calculated by the hash function. He also decided to manage the alteration status as shown in [Figure 12]. He makes a list of important source files managed by the server, and stores the hash value for each file, then compares the hash value in the file list with the original hash value on a regular basis','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2141,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','However, a security incident that has occurred between the check period cannot be detected by checking integrity periodically: The shorter the integrity check period, the better: However, if the number of files increases, creating and comparing hash values for each file increases the server load. Therefore, it\'s not an effective method, Introducing an integrity check technique that can detect an error at the kernel level in real time, is an alternative to the periodic integrity check method. That is, it is more effective to only run an integrity check once and check file alteration in real time whenever the file is executed or loaded into the memory to check whether the file has been tampered. In this way, loading the tampered executable file into memory can be prevented without constantly causing a CPU load. LCs \'L) 447s CiGOiosro The integrity of the message transmitted over the network is also a important security issue hacker can intercept and alter the transmitted message as shown in [Figure 13]. To check the integrity of the transmitted message, the sender creates a hash value for the message and transmits it along with the message. Upon receipt of the message, the receiver checks the integrity of the message and, if tampered, ignores the message. The hash function can be used in the form of a message authentication code (MAC), if authenticating the identity of the sender is not needed, and only the integrity of the data that has not been tampered transmission is needed. When the sender calculates the hash value the message as an input, it becomes a message authentication code. If this message authentication code is sent together with the message, the receiver can be confident that the message has not been tampered transmission: during using during','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2142,'646','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Encryption based on the password Both the hash function and encryption are techniques of the password effectively: However, there is a difference, in that the encryption algorithm can encrypt the unencrypted plaintext and then decrypt it again, whereas the hash function cannot find the original value of the hash function using the result value The hash function can be used for password-based encryption (PBE) In PBE, the hash value, which is obtained by entering the result of combining the password and salt (random number generated using & pseudo-random number generator) into the hash function, is used as an encryption Attacks against the password can be prevented using this method, hiding key: LiccCOiTC 316\" iuuic The hash function can be used for digital signatures: A digital signature is a method of providing both data integrity and the signature s authentication by performing a hash operation on a specific document, the signature s private Signing the entire message is very inefficient because the public operation should be repetitively performed on all message blocks Therefore, an electronic signature can be very efficiently generated by calculating a hash value for the message and signing on that value. Although the signer signed the hash value, instead of the message itself this signature is recognized as genuine signature for the message because another message with the same hash value is difficult: using key: key finding -','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2143,'647','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 14] User authentication',NULL,'6802c9b17fbe5.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b17fbe5.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2144,'647','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','User authentication refers to a function that enables the user to prove their identity to the other party over the network Given this, a third party should not be able to disguise as the user','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2145,'647','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','User authentication, also known as identification, is used to verify the identity of a user when logging in to a server, and to grant the authority of using information services. Servers should require the remote user to go through a strict authentication procedure because the remote user can perform all the privileges as the user in question,, once authenticated.','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2146,'648','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Message authentication is to check whether the contents of the transmitted message have the origina information and are not altered or modified. An electronic signature can be used to verify that the transmittec message has not be altered, and to identify the sender at the same time:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2147,'531','App\\Models\\Section','Text','Authentication refers to a method of verifying whether the information exchanged between the sender and receiver, who are the subject of the information, has not been altered or deleted, and whether the subject','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2148,'531','App\\Models\\Section','Text','(sender and receiver) is legitimate. That is, authentication can be divided into message authentication and user authentication:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2149,'649','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','his method is based on the user\'s information (\"What you know\"), and uses various means, such as a PIN \'ersonal Identification Number) , password, account number, etc,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2150,'650','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','This method is based on the user\'s possessions ( What you have\"), and uses various means, such as anOTP (One Time Password) , smart card, card etc key,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2151,'651','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','This method is based on the users body or characteristics of their body (What you are\"), and uses various means, such as iris recognition, fingerprint recognition, voice recognition, and face recognition','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2152,'532','App\\Models\\Section','Text','Authentication can be performed by the user\'s knowledge, the user\'s object, or the user\'s physical characteristics: using','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2153,'652','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 15] Vulnerabilities of the password authentication method',NULL,'6802c9b18f858.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b18f858.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2154,'652','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Overview of password authentication The user sets the password in advance. After that, the user is authenticated by comparing the password entered during authentication, with the set password. Although this authentication technology is the most widely it requires careful attention when using it because it is the most insecure as shown in [Figure 15]. used,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2155,'652','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Password policy abowvuiu poiey When creating a password, it should have at least 8 digits by combining uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters The user should be able to remember the password easily, but the attacker should have difficulty guessing it. Passwords should not be saved in plaintext, but should be saved using a hash function, rather than a two- way encryption algorithm: The authentication system should limit the number of failed login attempts. Attack techniques against the password Attack techniques against the password include brute force attacks, dictionary attacks, Trojan horses, direc access to the password file, social engineering techniques, etc countermeasures against passwora attacks Various countermeasures can be implemented, such as using a password generator, limiting the number login failures, changing passwords periodically, using an intrusion detection system (IDS) to detect dictionar attacks and brute force attacks, implementing security awareness training, an OTP etc, using','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2156,'653','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 7  Type of OTPs',NULL,'6802c9b1a04a7.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b1a04a7.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2157,'653','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 16] Operating procedure of the time-synchronous type',NULL,'6802c9b1b1a3a.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b1b1a3a.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2158,'653','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','An OTP is one of the methods used by the authentication system to authenticate users. This authenticatior technology uses a one-time password generator that generates and inputs a one-time password for each session. Type of OTPs The OTP can be largely classified into the synchronous and asynchronous types, as shown in <Table 7 Figure 16] shows the OTP operating procedure of the time-synchronous type','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2159,'654','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 8  Types of biometric authentication',NULL,'6802c9b1c4980.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b1c4980.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2160,'654','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 17] Process of biometric authentication',NULL,'6802c9b1d7d34.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b1d7d34.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2161,'654','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Cuccpl Ui DiuiicciiC auliiciicicaliui Authentication technology to extract the measurable physical or behavioral features of a person, using a automated sensor, and to use it as a means of authentication Characteristics of biometric authentication Universality: Each person must have the characteristic used by the system Distinctiveness: The characteristic must be distinguishable Acquisition: The characteristic can be measured and quantified from the sensor Permanence: The characteristic must not change or modify during the human life. Accuracy: The characteristic that requires authentication precision, regardless of environmental chang Acceptability: The acquisition phase should not be intrusive and the system should be user-friendly: Types of biometric authentication As shown in <Table 8 , the types of biometric authentication can be divided into method using body information and a method using behavioral characteristics. Frocess Or Diometric auinentication As shown in [Figure 17], the biometric authentication system consists of a \"biometric information registration system\" and a \"biometric authentication system\". The user\'s biometric information is stored in the biometric database in advance, and authentication is performed by comparing the data saved in the biometric information database, with the biometric information extracted from the user','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2162,'655','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 18] Concept of multi-factor authentication',NULL,'6802c9b1e9e0f.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b1e9e0f.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:49'),(2163,'655','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','As shown in [Figure 18], multi-factor authentication is a method of improving the security of authentication by combining multiple authentication technologies to supplement the weakness of a single authentication method: To implement a more powerful multi-factor authentication system, it is desirable to mix and use various authentication technologies, based on knowledge, ownership, and presence, such as OTP   fingerprint recognition:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2164,'656','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 19] Concept of the electronic signature',NULL,'6802c9b20981b.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b20981b.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2165,'656','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','An electronic signature is a technology that enables the user to sign on a electronic document using the authentication function of encryption technology, as shown in [Figure 19]. The effect of an electronic signature can be obtained by authenticating the identity of the signer, by using the authentication function of the public cryptographic technique, while authenticating a electronic document to be signed at the same time The basic assumption of the public encryption system is that the user (owner) will securely and secretly keep the private (secret key) , which becomes & of the public keys. If a certain signing operation is performed using the private key in this environment, it can only be performed by the user who has the private and the result can be recognized as the user s signature. The sender sends a message using public cryptographic techniques, together with an electronic signature, which is the result of encrypting the message digest (hash value of the message) with the private key: Then, the receiver checks the sender authentication, non-repudiation, and message integrity, by comparing the result of decrypting the sender\'s message, using the received electronic signature with the message digest tbat Wac calculetod hV Ucino  bo racoivad Onoccaoo key key key pair key, key lue','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2166,'657','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Forgery prevention: Anyone other than a legitimate signer shouldn\'t be able to the signature: User authentication: The signer should be identifiable from the electronic signature Non-repudiation: The signer should not be able to deny that the signer has signed the document Alteration prevention: A signed document should not be changeable Reuse prevention: A signature for one document cannot be reused as a signature for another document: forge','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2167,'658','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 9  Operation procedure of the electronic signature',NUL