ts it to the directory serverthen sends it to the user, via the RA The user stores the issued certificate in a hard disk or a removable disk of a PC and uses it in financial transactions and electronic commerce At this point, financial institutions verify the certificate by contacting the nublic CA [Fioure 201 shows the narticinants of the PKI and the workflow hetween them key key,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2174,'662','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 11  Operation steps of the sender and receiver',NULL,'6802c9b27230c.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b27230c.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2175,'662','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 21] Electronic signature and encryption processing procedure in the PKI',NULL,'6802c9b287cf3.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b287cf3.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2176,'662','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','[Figure 20] describes the process for user authentication and message confidentiality, and <Table 11  describes the main operation steps of the sender and receiver in the PKI environment,which is when both the sender and the receiver operate the public certificate encryption system. The session in [Figure 21] is a one-time secret generated by the sender, to apply the secret system to the message. The sender encrypts this using the public of the receiverto safely transmit it This encrypted session is called an electronic envelone key key, key key, key key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2177,'663','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 12  Main contents of the public key certificate',NULL,'6802c9b29aa49.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b29aa49.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2178,'663','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Public certificates are X Public certificates are issued by public CA by complying with the X.509 standard. Public certificates include the NPKI certificates, which are used by the for financial transactions and e-commerce transactions, and the GPKI certificate, which are used by administrative agencies for administrative work The certificate encryption system began to be advanced in 2011, and the length of the digital signature of the RSA algorithm has been increased from 1,024 bits to 2,048 bits The hash function was replaced by SHA-256 (a hash function producing a 256-bit value), instead of SHA-1 (a hash function producing a 160-bit value). <Table 12  shows the main contents included in the NPKI certificate key key public public key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2179,'664','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','CRL (Certiticate Revocation List) CRL refers to the list of certificates revoked by the CA The list contains the serial number, the revocation date, and the reasons for revocation According to RFC 3280, the certificate can be permanently revoked or temporarily held. The CRL should be periodically downloaded from the CRL distribution If the download is too long, revoked certificate can be used. If the cycle is too short, the overhead increases each time the certificate is used. point. cycle OCSP (Online Certiticate Status Protocol) This protocol makes up for the shortcomings that the CRL should be periodically updated. When the user attempts to access, the OCSP protocol immediately answers the validity of the certificate by requesting certificate status information in real time. The protocol is defined in RFC 6960, and generally uses a server configured with the HTTP gain','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2180,'665','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Access control refers to the task of controlling who can access a system, and which task the user can perform when the user interacts with the system. Specifically, access control consists of three parts: identification, authentication, and authorization. Identification process of identifying a subject its unique token, that is, process where the system identifies the subject: (e.g , ID, employee card, biometrics) using Authentication A process where the subject verifies its identity to the system, that is, a process where the system acknowledges the user who claims his/her identity password (knowledge-based) , certificate (ownership- based) , OTP (ownership-based), biometrics (presence-based)): (e.g:. Authorization A process when the system controls the task and object, which can be performed and accessed by the authenticated user (e.g, mandatory access control, discretionary access control, role-based access control):','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2181,'666','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 22] Procedure for performing access control',NULL,'6802c9b2a7527.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b2a7527.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2182,'666','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','An object can be accessed only when the right to access is obtained through the authorization process after identification and authentication.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2183,'667','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','This policy is called the \"need-to-know\" policy: System subjects should use the minimum amount of information that is needed for their activities. This policy has the effect of applying strong control over object access. However, sometimes this policy may impose excessive useless limitations on the legitimate subject.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2184,'668','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','This policy is based on the principle of maximum availability that is applied to increase the benefits of data sharing: That is, this policy can be effectively to the case when no special protection is needed, due to the high reliability of data exchange with the user: applied','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2185,'537','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The system security policy is the high-level instructions for designing and managingthe access control system: In general, the policy is the expression of the basic principles, desired by the organization, to protect target system resources That is, the access control principle defines the subject (who), time (when) , location (where) , object (what) , and behavior (how) that can be accepted or refused. The access control principle, which limits the scope of access, can be divided into the following two basic policies:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2186,'669','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 23] Mandatory access control',NULL,'6802c9b2b4073.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b2b4073.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2187,'669','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','A security level is given to the subject and security label is given to the object. Then, it is determined whether the subject in question can access the object, according to the predetermined rule. This policy is mainly used for military purposes A strong security system can be maintained, but its management efficiency is deteriorated.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2188,'670','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 24] Discretionary access control',NULL,'6802c9b2c25a1.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b2c25a1.png','2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:50'),(2189,'670','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Access to an object is controlled by the identity of the subject\'s account or the account\'s belonging group.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:36','2025-04-18 21:52:36'),(2190,'670','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The owner of the object determines access permission. This policy is mainly used for the system access control of Unix or Linux systems:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:37','2025-04-18 21:52:37'),(2191,'671','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 25] Role-based access control',NULL,'6802c9b2cf8d9.