en we try to use the Internet in our real life, such as for remote medical treatment and e-commerce, there are still several restrictions. Among those restrictions, security-related issues are most important and urgent: The most essential technology to protect internal information assets from various network security threats, include the firewall, virtual private network (VPN), and intrusion detection system (IDS): Things','',4,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2468,'53','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Learning objectives','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2469,'53','App\\Models\\Module','Text','To be able to classify the concepts and type of attacks through the network and to explain ho respond. To be able to describe network security technology and major solutions To be able to explain the wireless LAN security standard (IEEE.IIi) and security technology: To be able to explain the principle and application of SSL (Secure Socket Layer): To be able to explain and utilize security types and principles by application layer protocol.','',6,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2470,'53','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Keywords','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2471,'53','App\\Models\\Module','Text','Firewall, Virtual Private Network (VPN), SSL, traffic attack, denial of service (DOS) attack, Intrusion Detection System (IDS) , IPSec, transmission mode, tunnel mode, sniffing, spoofing, management, NAT, DMZ, WLAN, IEEE 802.11i, 4-way handshake, OWASP 10, anonymous FTP key top Building a secure network using the','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2472,'53','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Preview for practical business','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2473,'53','App\\Models\\Module','Text','Company A is a small and medium-sized company that utilizes a network connected to 90 computers. Currently, the company has 126 public IP addresses (211.82.50.0/25), one router (211.82.50.126/25), switch, database server, and a web server, respectively: In this situation, assistant manager, Kim, was instructed to introduce firewall to configure the external, internal, and DMZ network, in order to increase & network security level. Let\'s learn how to build a secure network under the following conditions, Set private IPs (192.168.1.0/24) for 90 internal PCs and the database server: Place the web server in the DMZ area, while keeping the existing address (211.82.50.1/25). Subnet the external network and DMZ network into two existing IP bands (211.83.50.0/25). Ic0 Ono ro Itor Ono firowa iitcn','',4,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2474,'776','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'6802c9b82cb0c.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b82cb0c.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2475,'776','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 54] Active attack',NULL,'6802c9b84296f.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b84296f.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2476,'776','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','X.8O0 divides security attacks into passive attacks and active attacks. A passive attack means that an attempt is made to obtain and exploit system information, but system resources are not affected. An active attack aims to change system resources and affect system operations. Passive attack passive attack refers to the eavesdropping or monitoring of transmitted data and is attempted to obtain the transmitted data. As shown in [Figure 53], passive attacks include message content disclosure and traffic attack Traffic attacks can also be made against encrypted data transmission for confidentiality: This attack estimates the nature of communication by observing the number and length of message exchanges: The passive attack has the characteristic that it is difficult to detect, because the attack does not data. Therefore, prevention is more important than detection: change','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2477,'776','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','(Source: W. Stallings, Cryptography and Network Security Principles and Practice, Prentice Hall, p.17) An active attack can be classified into masquerading, replay, modification of message, and denial of service (DOS) attack, which entail the illegal modification of transmitted data or the creation of false data. Masquerading occurs when one entity pretends to be another: In general, the masquerading attack is made together with one of the other active attack types The replay attack acquires one message, by using an inactive attack method, and sends the message to obtain unauthorized results. again','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2478,'776','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The modification of message attack obtains unauthorized results by illegallychanging parts of legal messages, delaying message transmission, or changing the message sequence. The denial-of-service attack interferes the normal use or management of communication equipment (specific computer or network). This attack is generally called a DoS attack Most of these attacks are made against a specific target The active attack has characteristics that are opposite to the passive attack It is very difficult to prevent active attacks completely, because all communication equipment and communication lines cannot be physically protected at all times. Response to active attacks aims to detect an attack and recover from the collanco dolav duo to cUch an atta','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2479,'776','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','(Source: W. Stallings, Cryptography and Network Security-Principles and Practice, Prentice Hall, p.18,19)','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2480,'777','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 55] Network security model',NULL,'6802c9b8540b1.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8540b1.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2481,'777','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','A computer network consists of communication objects, such as computers and communication systems of transmission devices and communication lines). The computer network exists to support data transmi: between the sending computer and receiving computer, regardless of the distance [Figure 55] is an abstract expression of network communication elements from the perspective of sec A single message is sent from the sender to the receiver through a network, like the Internet. communication subjects should cooperate with each other to exchange messages in this process. A lo information channel (a consisting of numerous communication devices is allocated between the ser computer and the receiving computer, which is used to transfer data) is established by setting the Int between the message source and destination, negotiating between the two communication subjects If transmission data needs to be protected from attacks on confidentiality and authentication, correspor security measures are started. All mechanisms for security should include the following two elements: Conversion, related to the security of the data to be sent, belongs to this For example, encryption mixes messages to prevent attackers from understanding the message or adding & code (hash code), on the message content to identify the sender belong to this. For example, encryption belong to this which are used to convert the message (confidential inform shared by two communicating subjects that is unknown to the attacker) before sending it, and to conve after receiving the message. path path keys again For example, encryption belong to this, which are used to convert the message (confidential information shared by two communicating subjects that is unknown to the attacker) before sending it, and to convert it after receiving the message keys again','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2482,'777','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','A trusted third party may be needed for secure transmission For example, a third party may distribute secret information, such as encryption to both communication subjects to prevent attackers from knowing it or may mediate a dispute when it occurs. A general network security model should meet the following four basic conditions when designing a specific security service: keys, Design should be an algorithm design that performs conversion related to security. An attacker should not be','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2483,'777','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Secret information, to be used by the conversion algorithm, should be created. A method for distributing and sharing confidential information should be developed. A security algorithm for a specific security service and a protocol, to be used by the two communicating entities that will use secret information, should be designated.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2484,'778','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 56] Network access security model',NULL,'6802c9b860189.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b860189.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2485,'778','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','An attacker tries to infiltrate into the information system to damage it or to destroy or steal personal information In addition, malware, such a5 a virus or worm, can infect the information system through the network Security response techniques against such unwanted access can be divided into two categories, as shown in [Figure 56]. The first category is the method of denying access to the information system, except for the authorized users, using the keeper function The in procedure using a password falls into this category: Once accessed by the user or software, the second-phase response is performed by the internal security control function. An intrusion detection system (IDS) that monitors the activity status of an information system and detects an intruder can be selected as the representative method of performing internal security control, log-| gate','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2486,'778','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','[Figure 56] Network access security model Stallings, Cryptography and Network Security-Principles and Practice, Prentice Hall, p.2 (Source: W. Stallings, Cryptography and Network Security-Principles and Practice, Prentice Hall, p.26)','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2487,'779','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 35  Protocols and functions of each layer of the OSI 7-layer reference model',NULL,'6802c9b873766.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b873766.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2488,'779','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 57] OSI 7-layer reference model',NULL,'6802c9b883627.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b883627.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2489,'779','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 58] TCPIIP protocol layer',NULL,'6802c9b8937c7.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8937c7.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2490,'779','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','[Figure 57] shows the OSI (Open System Interconnection) 7-layer reference model, described in the ISOJIEC 7498-1:1994(E) standard document, which indicates the interconnection structure between open systems: <Table 35  shows the protocols and functions corresponding to each layer of the OSI 7-layer reference model.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2491,'779','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The structure of the TCPIIP used for the ARPANET reference model that appeared earlier than the OSI 7-layer reference model and is composed of three layers, as shown in [Figure 56]. Application layer: Provides application services, including web (HTTP) , DNS, Telnet, FTP e-mail sending/ receiving (SMTPIPOPBJIMAP4), etc: This layer runs the services provided by the lower layer and the using','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2492,'779','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','transport layer: The concept of this layer includes, not only the application layer, but also the presentation layer and the session layer of the OSI reference model. Transport layer: Also known as the host-to-host transport layer This layer manages data exchange betweer irtual ports that are managed by the application program, such as the TCP, UDP, ad SCTP protocol. Thi ayer corresponds to the transport layer of the OSI reference model. Internet layer: Also known as the network layer, this layer manages the addressing and routing functions, and it corresponds to the network layer of the OSI reference model. The network interface layer in [Figure 58] is not a concept that is dependent o the structure of the TCPI IP protocol. It is also referred to as a network access layer The network interface layer is randomly selected by the network interface layer and practically transfers TCPIIP packets through a physical medium, such as IEEE 802.3 Ethernet or IEEE 802.11 Wi-Fi. This layer includes the functions of both the data link layer which manages the MAC function of the OSI 7-layer reference model, and the physical layer that defines electrical signals.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2493,'780','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 59] Security protocols by layer',NULL,'6802c9b8a0b76.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8a0b76.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2494,'780','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Since the purpose of designing the TCPIIP protocol structure lies in free information exchange, the concept of security is not considered in the design process. As TCPIIP is used as the core protocol of the Internet, and the application, like e-Commerce, is developed or used, protocols with security functions are added to','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2495,'780','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','the structure of the TCPIIP protocol. [Figure 59] shows security protocols by layer based on the OSI 7-layer reference model. Security protocols related to the application layer There are various security protocols related to the application layer such as PGP and SJMIME that provide e-mail security function, Kerberos that provides authentication functions, and SSH (secure shell) that supports secure remote access, etc Security protocois related tO tne transport Iayer SSL (Secure Socket Layer)[TLS (Transport Layer Security) is a protocol that acts above the transport layer which provides the secure transport layer services to the application layer TLS is the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard for SSL, and it provides end-to-end security and data integrity Security protocols related to the Internet The IPSec (IP Security) protocol that acts above the Internet layer, which provides security features, such as authentication and encryption, to the Internet layer This protocol is used to implement VPN services','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2496,'781','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The DoS attack disturbs the normal operation of a specific server by causing various types of load. It is a attack on availability, one of the security services Typical DoS attacks include land attacks, ping of death attacks, Syn flooding attacks, and Boink attacks Laliu allack An attack that sends a packet to the target, by making the IP address of the source and destination identical to the attackers IP address. Server operation fails, due to serious failure in the IP protocol stack because the host that receives the packet falls into an infinite of receiving and sending the packet This attack can be responded to by blocking packets whose source IP address is the same as the server\'s IP address, among the packets flowing into the network, using a router or packet filtering tool. loop Fing Ui ueaui allack When an attacker makes an ICMP packet that much larger than the normal size and sends it, the packet is divided into many small fragments and transmitted to the attacking network. Accordingly, the attack target','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2497,'781','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','system must process all those small packets. As a result, it takes a lot more load than the normal Ping command, and the performance of the system is degraded This attack can be responded to by blocking ICMP protocols, which sends the command, using a firewall and other devices. Ping Syn flooding attack Syn flooding attacks exploit the vulnerability that half-open connection can establish during the 3-way handshaking process (TCP connection setup process) . The system, under this attack, can no longer accept connection requests outside: Therefore, normal services cannot be provided. Not only Windows systems, but all systems that provide TCP-based services on the Internet (for example, web server, FTP server, mail server, etc), can be damaged by this attack This attack can be responded to by reducing the waiting time of the SYN reception status in the target system, or by installing an intrusion prevention system from DuiIK allack The Boink attack is a DoS attack that modifies Boink. Assuming that the packet size is 100 bytes, is sent as the sequence number (which is the byte number) of the first packet. After that, 101 is sent as the sequence number of the next packet, and 201 is normally sent as the next packet. Then, 2002 is abnormally sent as the 2Oth packet, and 101 is normally sent as the 2Ist packet: Then, 2002 is abnormally sent as the 22nd packet, and so on. As a result, the overload of repeatedly sending and combining packets is to the attack target system: The countermeasures against this attack are similar to those against the ping of dead attack or Syn flooding attack applied The DDoS (Distributed DOS) attack is the evolved type of the DoS attack The DDoS attack is a DoS attack that has multiple attack sources.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2498,'782','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Sniffing is based on the concept of eavesdropping, etc, and is also known as a passive attack All systems connected to the Internet, that is, LAN, have an IP address (layer 3 address) and a MAC (medium access control) address (layer 2 address) implemented in a network interface card. Since every MAC address on the Internet has a different value, each system can be uniquely identified. All hosts on the same LAN share the same communication line. Therefore, computers on the LAN can view all the communication traffic of other computers. Due to this characteristic, network interface cards (commonly referred to as LAN cards) have a filtering function that ignores a without its own MAC address. This filtering function ensures that only traffic with its own MAC address can be received. However, users can set the function that enables all traffic to be viewed, using the LAN card in case of special circumstances, which is called promiscuous mode Sniffing is a attack that eavesdrops on all traffic on a specific LAN, by setting the LAN card to promiscuous mode. When a LAN uses a switch, traffic is sent to a specific destination computer: Therefore, even if the LAN card is set to promiscuous mode, traffic of other destinations cannot be received. In this case, sniffing can be performed using the method of switch jamming, ARP redirect, ICMP redirect, MAC spoofing, etc frame','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2499,'782','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Since all sniffers eavesdrop on the network by setting their LAN cards to promiscuous mode, a system running sniffer program can be detected by periodically checking if a specific host is set in promiscuous mode. ARP, DNS, or induction method can be used for detection: Ping,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2500,'783','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 60] ARP spoofing',NULL,'6802c9b8abe5f.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8abe5f.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2501,'783','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Spoofing is the act of disguising and can apply to anything related to communication, such as the IP address, host name, port number, MAC address, etc. A spoofing attack technique is used to attack other target systems by disguising its own identification information. The spoofing attack is used for other attacks, such as packet sniffing, DoS attack and session hijacking: ARP spoofing The ARP protocol maps IP addresses and MAC addresses, whereas ARP spoofing attacks trick MAC addresses. As shown in [Figure 60], the attacker first informs the client of the fake MAC address \"CC , corresponding to the server (address: 10.0.0.2) and notifies the server of the fake MAC address \"CC , corresponding to the client (address: 10.0.0.3). Since an attacker notifies its own MAC address to the other communication party (server and client computer) , both the sever and the client send packets to the attacker After the attacker reads the packets received from the server and the client, the server normally sends the packets that the server sends to the client, and the packets that the client sends to the server (As a result,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2502,'783','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','There are no fundamental countermeasures against ARP spoofing, because it\'s the problem of the TCPIIP protocol structure itself However, the change of the MAC address can be prevented by setting the attributes of the ARP table, using the arp command to prevent the change of the ARP table. To use this method, the setting command should be executed every time the system is rebooted An IP spoofing attack hacks the host by changing its IP address. That is, an attacker steals the IP address of other users and illegally obtains the rights to on or others. log','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2503,'783','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Two systems, A and B, that are in a trusted relationship in the network environment can use a service that enables the user to into system B using the system A account, which is called trust authentication Authentication is performed by the trust service on the network based on the network address, not the password. That is, the server stores the trusted client IP addresses and allows log-in without an ID and password, if the client with the saved IP address requests in, To respond to IP spoofing, it is recommended not to use trust authentication, except under special circumstances log log-1 DNS spoofing D0 Ppoi6 If an attacker takes control of the DNS server of a certain domain, the user can be connected to the system designated by the attacker because the user finally obtains that IP address even though the user intended to obtain the IP address of the other system. That is, the attacker sniffs the DNS, designated by the user, to request address translation and traffic from the higher-level DNS site that gives the response, and it passes the IP address of the attacker\'s intended site as the final response. To respond to DNS spoofing, the IP address of the important access server can be registered in the host file, so the IP address can be obtained without querying the DNS server: However, it is realistically impossible to register and manage the IP addresses of all servers.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2504,'784','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The IPv4 (Internet Protocol version 4) has no authentication function and is vulnerable to attacks, such as eavesdropping or packet alteration IPsec (Internet Protocol Security) was developed to make up for the security vulnerability of IP IPSec provides security functions to all application programs because it supports the safe operation of the IP, by providing encryption and authentication services to the IP by packet unit. IPsec encompasses three functional areas: authentication, confidentiality, and management: It is optional in Ipv4, but implemented as a basic function in IPv6. key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2505,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 36  Communication phase in the IPSec environment',NULL,'6802c9b8be5ad.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b8be5ad.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2506,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 61] IPSec operation',NULL,'6802c9b8d303a.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8d303a.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2507,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'(Source: W. Stallings, Network Security Essentials, Pearson, p.272)',NULL,'6802c9b8e27db.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8e27db.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2508,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'6802c9b8f1f64.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b8f1f64.png','2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:56'),(2509,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','[Figure 61] shows that when an organization uses the LAN distributed in several places, IP traffic is transmitted within the LAN, but outgoing traffic of the LAN is transmitted using IPSec protocol for safe communication. The IPSec protocol runs on the device, such as the router or firewall, which is transparently visible to the computers on the LAN: [Figure 62] shows the structure of IPSec IPSec is largely composed of Internet Exchange (IKE) for Security Association (SA) negotiation, a repository of Sas Security Association Database (SAD), Security Policy Database (SPD) that stores security policies that define how IP traffic is associated with a specific SA, AH (Authentication Header) protocol, providing an actual authentication service, and the Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) protocol, providing authentication and encryption services. Key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2510,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Transport mode and tunnel mode AH and ESP support transport mode or tunnel mode. As shown in [Figure 63], IP headers do not change ar only the payload of the IP datagram is encrypted in transport mode, whereas all IP datagrams are encrypte and transmitted as the payload of a new IP packet in tunnel mode In general, the router plays a proxy role IPSec in tunnel mode The transport mode is mainly used to protect the upper layer protocol, which is the payload range of the datagram: For example, it is used to protect TCP fragmentation or ICMP packets. IPSec in transport moc operates right above the IP layer ESP encrypts the IP payload, but it does not encrypt the IP header transport mode, and authentication is optional. AH only authenticates the IP payload and selected parts the IP header in transport mode: Tunnel mode protects all IP datagrams. To this end, an \'external\" IP datagram that has a new external header is created. No router can inspect the internal IP header while this datagram is transported. For th reason the IP datagram can be transported to the external network, through a conceptual tunnel, usir tunnel mode ESP in tunnel mode encrypts all internal IP datagrams, including the internal IP header, and authenticatic is optional. AH in tunnel mode authenticates all internal IP datagrams and selected parts of the external header','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2511,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Figure 63] Encryption of transmission mode and tunnel mode [Figure 63] Encryption of transmission mode and tunnel mode Source: W. Stallings, Network Security Essentials, Pearson, p.285) Jccuiil) Aosociccioi[ (J To establish secure communication with the other party, IPSec, authentication and encryption algorithms to be used by two communication entities, as well as encryption keys, are needed The security algorithm and information should be exchanged and saved before full-scale communication, and the records of this information are called SA Since there are many SAs in one system, SAs are identified by the security parameter index (SPI) , which is given randomly, and a destination IP address.  Since one SA is needed using key','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2512,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','for secure communication in one direction, two SAs are needed for two communication entities in order to establish two-way communication. <Table 36  shows the communication process between system A and B, while the SA is stored. It is assumed that system A initiates communication in this table.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2513,'785','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','management of IPSec includes the cryptographic determination and distribution function Four are needed for communication between two applications. That is, a of the sending and receiving keys is needed for integrity and confidentiality: Let IKE create ad store the SA through secure authentication between two applications to enable IPSec communication by exchanging messages IKE defines procedures and packet formats to establish, negotiate, modify, and remove the SA Key key keys pair','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2514,'786','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','blementing VPN and IPSec, using IPSec, also provides security for application layer services, such as secure note access, e-commerce security, etc,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2515,'787','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','SSL IS a protocoi aeveiopea DY ietscape s HicKman in 1994 ana stanaaraizea Dy tne internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) after the SSL version 3.0 and named as TLS (Transport Layer Security). Most web browsers support SSL. The SSL protocol is positioned between the application layer and the transport layer in the TCP/ IP protocol structure: The protocol is designed to use TCP to provide reliable end-to-end secure services: Even though SSL can be used in various application layer protocols, it is actually most widely used by the HTTP application When HTTP uses SSL, it is called HTTPS. The two important concepts of SSL are connection and session: SSL connection: SSL connection refers to transport providing appropriate services A connection in SSL is a peer-to-peer relationship and is temporary, and all connections are associated with one session: SSL session: An SSL session refers to an association between a client and a server, To start a session, the','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:46','2025-04-18 21:52:46'),(2516,'787','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','handshake protocol should be used, which will be described below: A session defines cryptographic security parameters that are shared by multiple connections, which is used to avoid negotiating required new security parameters for each connection:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2517,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 37  Function of the SSL protocol',NULL,'6802c9b91258b.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b91258b.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2518,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 38  Operation by phase of the SSL protocol',NULL,'6802c9b926f69.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b926f69.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2519,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 64] Composition of the SSL protocol',NULL,'6802c9b934d40.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b934d40.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2520,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 65] Operating procedure of the SSL protocol',NULL,'6802c9b944fe0.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b944fe0.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2521,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Structure of the SSL protocol As shown in [Figure 64], SSL is composed of four protocols, including handshake, change cipher Spec, record and alert.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2522,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Type ot SSL protocols <Table 37  shows the functions by SSL protocol type.','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2523,'788','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Operating procedure of the SSL protocol [Figure 65] shows the main operating procedure of the SSL protocol, and <Table 38  shows the operating details of each phase.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2524,'789','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 39  Checking SSL application',NULL,'6802c9b955030.png','/storage/tables/6802c9b955030.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2525,'789','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Installing an SSL certiticate in the server An SSL certificate should be installed in the web server to apply SSL. A certificate signature request document,, called CSR (Certificate Signing Request) should be created and requested to the certification authority after creating a private key in the running web server Then, an SSL certificate should be received from the certification authority and installed in the web server in order to set the web server If the SSL accelerator is used, the certificate can also be installed in the SSL accelerator','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2526,'789','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','How to check SSL application Table 39  describes how to check the SSL installed in the web server','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2527,'789','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Consideration on the load atter SSL application Various computing tasks created during the SSL handshake process put a heavy workload on the CPU. The SSL accelerator is a solution released to solve such a heavy workload on the CPU. The SSL accelerator can be installed on the server as a separate PCI card or dedicated equipment Recently, since the web accelerator and L4 switch provide an SSL accelerator as a separate function, only a separate SSL accelerator license needs to be purchased. The connection URL and the URL included in the web application source should be changed to \"https:Ir\' after applying SSL. In addition, the web application response speed can be improved when the SSL load of the static content, such as images, JavaScript, CSS (CascadingStyleSheets), etc. is increased, using an SSL web browser cache or a web accelerator','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2528,'600','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 66] Extended service set of IEEE 802.11',NULL,'6802c9b963259.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b963259.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2529,'600','App\\Models\\Section','Text','Since incoming and outgoing data is broadcast in the air in the wireless LAN, radio waves, the data is exposed to all wireless LAN users while it is being transmitted. The use of wireless LAN is increasing rapidly because it has various advantages and convenience However, security is more vulnerable than wired LAN because of the characteristic of radio waves as communication medium. Therefore, security should be considered more seriously: In particular, there is a high possibility of various security incidents in the environment that is opened to the public, like a wireless LAN: Therefore, security should be taken into account [Figure 66] shows the structure of the general WLAN, defined by the IEEE 802.11. In this figure, the Basic Service Set (BSS) is a unit composed of stations (STAs) that compete for access to the same wireless medium, while running with the same MAC protocol. And the extended service set refers to an environment in which multiple basic service sets can be connected to a distribution system in order to communicate with each other: using using public (Source: W. Stallings, Network Security Essentials, Pearson, p.180)','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2530,'790','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','There are various types of attacks in the technical security threat of the wireless LAN, including the of important user information through radio wave collection, illegal access, and man in the middle attack, jamming, denial of service attack using large packet transmission, and hacking weak security settings, such as WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) to illegally access and infiltrate into the internal network Most technical security threats to wireless LAN can be blocked by setting security features provided by the wireless AP (Access Point), such as WPA2 (Wi-Fi Protected Access2) . However, when using a wireless LAN in place where important information is handled, such as in a corporate environment, a professional wireless security system, such as WIPS (Wireless Intrusion Prevention System) must be introduced. leakage','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2531,'791','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','A strong security technology can be easily bypassed if the threat is not properly managed, even though the technology is applied to the wireless LAN. Administrative security threats include insufficient management of wireless LAN equipment and devices, intrusion, due to a lack of user security awareness, and allowing outsiders to access internal APs and insiders to access external Aps, due to insufficient radio wave management. To respond to the administrative security threat of wireless LAN, management plans for access devices and terminals, such as Aps, should be established and implemented, user awareness should be raised periodically, should be implemented, and illegal internal and external accesses should be checked. Itraining','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2532,'792','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Most network devices in the wired LAN environment are installed and managed in a place that is difficult to access by general users. On the contrary, most of the wireless AP are exposed and installed outside because radio waves should be transmitted. In this case, the wireless AP is exposed to risks, such as theft and damage, power shutdown, LAN cable separation, etc, so service failure may occur: Also, if the wireless device is lost and stored WLAN access information and security setting information is leaked, unauthorized persons can access the wireless LAN. To prepare for such a threat,, it should be ensured that the wireless AP is not exposed to the outside, setting information should be changed periodically, and a method of managing devices that use the WLAN, along with a loss prevention plan, should be devised.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2533,'601','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'6802c9b972c8b.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b972c8b.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2534,'601','App\\Models\\Section','Text','Since wireless LAN communication uses radio waves, physical access control on the communication mediun is impossible Therefore, anyone can use wireless LAN services and various security threats can be caused b_ radio wave collection and disturbance. [Figure 67] shows various security threats in the wireless LAN:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2535,'601','App\\Models\\Section','Text','(Source: Baek Jonghyeon, Domestic Wi-Fi Security Status and Guide to Safe Wireless LAN Usage, TTA Journal)','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2536,'793','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','NEP was developed to reinforce the security functions of IEEE 802.11 (wireless LAN standard): Jowever, it is exposed to various attack techniques, such as the brute force attack due to insufficient security eatures. Accordingly, the 802.11i working group has developed various functions to solve the security problem )f the wireless LAN. features. Accordingly, the 802.11i working group has developed various functions to solve the security problem of the wireless LAN. To protect wireless LAN users, the IEEE 802.11i standard defines user authentication, key exchange, and advanced wireless section encryption algorithms It also satisfies standardization goals by implementing IEEE To protect wireless LAN users, the IEEE 802.11i standard defines user authentication, exchange, and advanced wireless section encryption algorithms. It also satisfies standardization by implementing IEEE key goals','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2537,'793','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','802.1X authentication, 4-way handshake exchange, and CCMP (Counter Mode With CBC-MAC Protocol) encryption algorithm, as essential functions. key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2538,'794','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'6802c9b984bae.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b984bae.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2539,'794','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'(b) Cryptographic algorithms',NULL,'6802c9b9920a1.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b9920a1.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2540,'794','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The security standard of IEEE 802.1i defines the following services. [Figure 68] Shows the structure of the security protocol and encryption protocol used to provide these services. Authentication: The user and the authentication server (AS) should authenticate with each other using the protocol, and a temporary to be used between the client and the AP on the wireless link, should be generated. key, Access control: Proper message routing and exchange should be performed using the authentication function This function can be performed together with various authentication protocols. Privacy through message integrity: MAC layer data is encrypted together with message integrity code, to guarantee that it is not been tampered with: key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2541,'794','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','[Figure 68] IEEE 802.11i components Source: W. Stallings, Network Security Essentials, Pearson, p.184)','',4,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2542,'795','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','EC OUZ.| operaion May valy depenaing On tre cortiguralion ana uevice 01 le WVLAIV ara Can De uesciided y a five-s operation, as shown in [Figure 69]. 1) Search: The STA that wants communication, searches for the desired WLAN AP to generate an SA with an AP, using the function that the AP broadcasts security policies. 2) Authentication: The STA and AS (authentication server) authenticate with each other At this time, the AP only transfers communication data between the STA and the AS, step','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2543,'797','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','generation and distribution: In this phase, the AS transfers PMK (Pairwise Master Key) to the AP of the STA using the distribution protocol, based on RADIUS (Remote Authentication Dial-In User Services, After that, the AP and STA generate and share the cryptographic by exchanging messages using the Key key key, ) Secure data transmission: The STA and the other partys end station securely exchange frames using the AP In this case, data is only transmitted between the STA and the AP ) Disconnection: The secure connection of the AP and the STA is released by exchanging messages, and the ina connactionic roctoro','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2544,'799','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 69] IEEE 802.1Ii operation steps',NULL,'6802c9b9a035c.png','/storage/figures/6802c9b9a035c.png','2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:57'),(2545,'799','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','[Figure 69] IEEE 802.1II operation steps rce: W. Stallings, Network Security Essentials, Pearson, p.185)','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-18 21:52:47','2025-04-18 21:52:47'),(2546,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Recent Trends and Major Issues','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2547,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Text','In the past, the perception of IT among the business community was that IT could play a auxiliary role in business processes, but that nothing more could be expected from it: However, as digital technologies have become ever more deeply embedded in users\' lifestyles, IT is actively integrated into corporate business processes It is this perspective that people must understand not only the concept of (IT?) business but also the IT ecosystem and IT value chain related to IT business. being from','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2548,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Learning Objectives','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2549,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Text','1. To be able to explain the concept of IT business and its characteristics. 2 To be able to the IT business ecosystem 3. To be able to explain the business value chain after understanding the IT resources allocated to businesses and the activities (roles/functions?) of such IT resources: explain','',4,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2550,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Keywords','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2551,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Text','oncept of IT business, IT business ecosystem, IT business value chair','',6,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2552,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Header','K Preview for practical business','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2553,'54','App\\Models\\Module','Text','Alibaba, a Chinese e-commerce company, was listed on the New York Stock Exchange on the morning of September 19, 2014. What\'s amazing about Alibaba is that on the of its its stock price rose by 38 percent to $231.4 billion (241.6 trillion won) in market value, and Jack Ma, Alibaba\'s largest shareholder, quickly became China s richest man, with $25 billion (26 trillion won) in assets In 1999, Jack Ma, along with seventeen friends, founded Alibaba, an online shopping mall that sells Chinese SME products to companies around the world from his apartment . Alibaba s rapid growth began in 2000 with a $20 million investment from Softbank\'s Masa) Son Following in the footsteps of Alibaba a B2B service, the company launched \"Taobao,\" an online shopping mall for individuals (C2C) , tmall.com\" an online department store for wealthy customers, and \"Alipay,\" an electronic payment service Alibaba Group has become the world s leading online shopping mall and fintech corporation. Alibaba is also one of the finest models of success in the IT business So what is the success factor (CSF) that has enabled the company to out-maneuver eBay, the global company that previously occupied the dominant position in the day listing, yoshi Today, key First, there are no transaction fees at Alibaba\'$ online shopping mall. Profits are generated from advertising and search services Second, the company deployed an innovative logistics system that can deliver goods to any address in the vast Chinese territory injust 1~2 and, using the \'Alipay service, it turned China\'s unreliable e-commerce into a trading channel trusted by the trading parties Third, it worked aggressively to meet customer requirements It supported the practice of \'chat-purchase\' when shopping through the Internet, whereby customers can negotiate the price of a product by chatting before making a purchase decision: Fourth, CEO Ma Yun\'s vision and strategy inspired his employees to dedicate themselves to the company and drove them to work with all have got days, they As we saw earlier Alibaba provides the three elements of competitiveness that all companies must have: price, quality, and customer-friendly services. And, most importantly, the organization is very well led by the CEO thanks to his vision and strategy   Alibaba is a perfect example of why strategy is so important in the hucinecc','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2554,'603','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'(a) IT utilization',NULL,'68039ada7c33b.png','/storage/figures/68039ada7c33b.png','2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:45:14'),(2555,'603','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'68039adab1861.png','/storage/figures/68039adab1861.png','2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:45:14'),(2556,'603','App\\Models\\Section','Text','IT business refers to all activities that are strategically carried out by integrating IT into a broad range of processes tc realize the business objectives of a company: In the twentieth century, computers were installed mainly in computing rooms and used only sparingly in the ordinan} working environment of most businesses However, since the 1990s, with the development of computers ad the mass adoption of web technology, the use of computers has gradually been extended to the ordinary working oni iironmant This popularization of computer technology accelerated rapidly in the twenty-first century with the infiltration of IT into every corner of the national industries From this point on,, the lifestyle of the great majority of people began to transition to one centered on digital technologies, and IT began to play a key role in the business processes of almost all industries In other words, companies were not utilizing computers only partially in the workplace, rather IT began to play a key role in companies\' decision-making process from an enterprise-wide perspective to piay a key roie In companies aecision-making process Trom an enterprise-wiae perspective: Around 2005, the concept of \'IT business\' first began to be discussed and recognized in earnest by people working in the field, mainly in industries that sell products where IT is critical. After 2010,as a growing number of companies integrated IT into their business processes, the concept of IT business evolved into a structure in which IT is tightly merged with business processes in order to give companies a competitive advantage In particular decision-makers in the world of business began to recognize the importance of fully incorporating IT into their businesses in order to acquire high-quality data in a rapidly changing business environment: [Fig: 2] explains how the concept of IT business bac ouoOd cortko Vcarc','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2557,'605','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Fig.2] The evolving concept of IT business',NULL,'68039adae29a5.png','/storage/figures/68039adae29a5.png','2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:45:14'),(2558,'605','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Fig.4] The strategic links between business and IT',NULL,'68039adb08f5d.png','/storage/figures/68039adb08f5d.png','2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:45:15'),(2559,'605','App\\Models\\Section','Text','In terms of IT business, IT is more than just a tool or a support function: It is becoming established as a concept whose interdependence with business strategy objectives and processes is maximized. This maximization of interdependence not only strengthens the competitiveness of a company\' s business model but also plays a major role in creating new business value: [Figure 3] shows the interdependence between a coprorate business &nd the IT system of a corporation.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2560,'605','App\\Models\\Section','Text','In IT business, the alignment of business and IT can be understood as IT application programs, IT infrastructure, and an IT organization that supports ad realizes a companysbusiness strategy and business processes The strategic alignment model of business and IT can be represented as a 2-dimensional diagram, as shown in [Fig: 4]. In this figure, the\"strategic fit\" dimension is subdivided into external focus (business environment) and internal focus (management structure), while the\"functional integration\" dimension is subdivided into business and IT','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2561,'605','App\\Models\\Section','Text','To achieve strategic alignment,, this model defines four areas that complement each other: business strategy, strategy, organizational infrastructure ad processes IT infrastructure, and processes Each area has its own scope capabilities, goverance, infrastructure, processes, and technology:','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:44:34'),(2562,'213','App\\Models\\Lesson','Figures',NULL,'[Fig.1] IT Business Lifecycle and Interrelationship Diagram',NULL,'68039adb39799.png','/storage/figures/68039adb39799.png','2025-04-19 12:44:34','2025-04-19 12:45:15'),(2563,'213','App\\Models\\Lesson','Text','An IT business is pursued as a series of steps after developing a strategy ad establishing a plan for adopting & IT business The IT business process begins right after the adoption of the IT business. The ultimate output of this process is an IT business service that will generate earnings for the company: This cycle then \"recycles\" itself perpetually as IT becomes integrated into the companys business Thereafter the direction of the IT business can be corrected or improved by evaluating its performance on a continuous basis. The management environment surrounding a company responds with sensitivity to changes in politics, economy, society, culture, and technology: Further, the management environment evolves continuously to become fully optimized for the objective of maximizing corporate value As a core element for optimizing the management of a company, ITs integration with the service (which utilizes the latest technologies) sets the direction in which the IT hucinocc Willevolo','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2564,'213','App\\Models\\Lesson','Text','To efficiently plan and implement an IT business and realize the benefits of its implementation, the concept of IT business must first be clearly established.  Therefore, this chapter begins by explaining the concept of IT business and how it has evolved. Next, we will introduce an IT ecosystem made up of contents (C), platform (P) , network (N), device (D) , and security (S) industries that compete and collaborate with each other in the IT business environment (an environment which is affected by the new IT technology hype curve) ad the IT value chain produced by the ecosystem','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2565,'606','App\\Models\\Section','Text','TvuvV icls lanc a iuK al Uie Ciiaige) m Lie |  leci m iuisy eiiviuiticiil lial iave diuus i abuul vaiiuu) | | Dusiic55 innovations in recent times A diagram that shows changes in the expected level of industrial economic value and the impact of new technologies in the IT sector over time is what the hype cycle from Gartner (released every year) is all about. In the hype cycle, the so-called \"innovation trigger\" is the time when new technologies are first introduced and people expect great from them: After that point, the level of expectation gradually increases before the new technology starts to become more exaggerated than what it can actually deliver leading to a period when the bubble reaches its maximum size (the peak of inflated expectations): The Trough of Disillusionment is the period when the bubble bursts, after which the hype cycle enters a of revival (the Slope of Enlightenment) in which the expectations for the technology start to climb steadily once In the last period of the hype the technology transitions to the Plateau of Productivity, the period when it generates steady values things period again. cycle,','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2566,'608','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The hype cycle allows us to understand not only those technologies which have recently become important issues but also what kind of world will unfold in the future due to the nature of such technologies Understanding the evolution of technology as presented in the hype cycle and incorporating it into an IT business can be of tremendous help to a companys growth','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2567,'609','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'<TableI IT paradigm change',NULL,'68039adb60c1f.png','/storage/tables/68039adb60c1f.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:15'),(2568,'609','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'',NULL,'68039adba242c.png','/storage/tables/68039adba242c.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:15'),(2569,'609','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Fig6] CPNDS ecosystem and ICBM core technology of the IT industry',NULL,'68039adbca4da.png','/storage/figures/68039adbca4da.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:15'),(2570,'609','App\\Models\\Section','Text','As IT technology continues to advance ad improve, it is creating a huge ecosystem Where different technologie both interact with and compete each other: [Fig: 6] represents this IT ecosystem: against Dul ilc  aCl Wvili alu cumpele againisl CaCit Ul ICI. [7g Oj tepiesciils Uis || Clusysleit After the Information Revolution of the 1980s brought on by the development of personal computer and telecom networks, we witnessed-from around the year 2000 onwards the birth of the Smart Revolution in which mobile devices began to be converged with smartphone-based wireless Internet, phone, and computing services The Smart Revolution not only accelerated the convergence of the IT industry but also affected other industries, acting as a catalyst for the overall \"smartification\" of entire industries Overall smartification has resulted in IT technology being adopted by such diverse sectors as education, automobiles defense, construction, shipbuilding, and medicine. Advances in sensor and network technologies are driving the','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2571,'609','App\\Models\\Section','Text','transformation of MZM (Machine to Machine) into the loT (Internet of Things) and extending it to the realm the Internet of Everything (IoE) IT technology is connecting humans to humans, humans to objects, and object to objects, and leading our society towards a hyper-connected society where humans, objects, spaces, data, anc services are all connected together','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2572,'609','App\\Models\\Section','Text','A hyper-connected society wields a huge influence on the IT ecosystem, which is built on contents, platforms networks, devices, and security As the center of the IT ecosystem moves hardware devices to platforms anc contents, software is becoming increasingly important, and smart mobile-based IT convergence is expanding intc traditional major industries, finance, and healthcare from Meanwhile, destructive innovations like 3D printing ad unmanned vehicles with the capacity to destroy existing markets are leading the IT ecosystem ad improving competitiveness based on open innovation, ad demand customized business models ae proliferating The core technology that is currently making the hyper-connected society possible is ICBM technology, Which consists of the Interet of Things (loT), Cloud Computing, Big Data, and mobile. [Table 1] explains the changes place in the IT technology environment and the form of IT competition in terms of the following five major trends from the perspective of IT paradigm change: the change from HW to SW platforms, the change IT convergence to smart convergence, the ICBM-based hyper-connected society, the changes in the IT technology environment and the IT business transformation of competition taking from rapid','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2573,'610','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'<Table2  Components of an IT business ecosystem',NULL,'68039adc485d9.png','/storage/tables/68039adc485d9.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2574,'610','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'',NULL,'68039adc74189.png','/storage/tables/68039adc74189.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2575,'610','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The table below describes the characteristics of the 5 components (contents, platform, network, device, and security) that constitute an IT ecosystem:','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2576,'610','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The sophistication and smartification of IT cyber threats is leading to an increase in damages and threats due tothe increased use of IT by key national infrastructures There is a growing threat of cyber targeted attacks such as cyber terrorism,, which aims to neutralize information and communication networks and computer systems, and hacktivism,in Security (S) which hackers attack computer systems for political and social purposes The response to new malicious hacking attacks is changing from a response based on security technology for post-attack investigations to one based on security technology for early','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2577,'611','App\\Models\\Section','Text','Tne concept Of T resources encompasses tne peopie, processes, sortware ana naraware used tO run anl business IT resources include IT support systems and IT management systems, of which the former are systems that support or manage IT businesses, such as ERP (Enterprise Resource Management) , SCM (Supply Chain Management)and PLMProduct Lifecycle Management) while the latter IT typically include information technology service management (ITSM): IT resources evolve continuously while maintaining a direct relationship with the IT business in question. They are changing in a direction that maximizes the results of an IT business with changing technologies ad the changing times. The system for managing IT resources is called an IT resource management system: Essentially, it manages and controls the solutions, products, and processes required to support IT businesses The IT resource management system manages resources (from planning and development through application, operation and management to disposal) using the IT resource lifecycle as a template It manages the specification list of IT resources as well as the gains in business performance achieved by utilizing IT resources','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2578,'800','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','companies are using their IT resources to improve their overall production efficiency: For example, most domestic hypermarkets in South Korea monitor customer purchasing patterns in realtime, and manage their Many','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2579,'800','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','inventory levels continuously based on information gleaned the customers\' purchasing data. The inventory data are sent to a process that analyzes real-time customer purchasing patterns This pursuit of production efficiency can maximize sales and contribute significantly to the building of competitive advantages Wal-Mart is a case in point: The company recorded sales of more than $28 per unit area of the store (which is more than double that of other retailers (sales of $12 per unit area on average) through the use of its RetaiLink system, which allows suppliers to access Wal-Mart\'s data warehouse directly: from','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2580,'801','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Since the dawn of the twenty-first century, we have been seeing ever more examples of new business values being created through the application of IT resources. Apple completely changed the offline music distribution structure with its iTunes music store: The new online music distribution structure has created a new business value, and this is considered by many to have been the greatest driver of Apples growth as a company: E-commerce is also another example of a new business value created by IT resources. The virtual online market that emerged through IT is changing the traditional concept of commerce, spawning new concepts of commerce such as open markets and social commerce','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2581,'802','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Many companies today are seeking new markets and global businesses to develop for the sake of their survival and prosperity: The global cooperative working environment enabled by IT resources has presented possibilities for exploring new markets to companies that otherwise would have kept their focus on local markets only: The global cooperative working environment has challenged traditional ideas about the costs, labor, ad time needed for developing global businesses For example, the establishment of videoconferencing systems has improved decision-making speed and efficiency in the rapidly changing business environment, while the ability to exchange information through Intranet systems without the constraints of time and space has given huge competitive advantages to global businesses','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2582,'612','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Fig: 7] The role of IT resources',NULL,'68039adc8d20d.png','/storage/figures/68039adc8d20d.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2583,'612','App\\Models\\Section','Text','One can identify the many benefits to be derived the use of IT resources for an IT business, but they can summarized into three main viewpoints from','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2584,'613','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'8] The cyclical management of IT business [Fig',NULL,'68039adca1223.png','/storage/figures/68039adca1223.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2585,'613','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Fig 9] The management and control structure of an IT business',NULL,'68039adcb47f9.png','/storage/figures/68039adcb47f9.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2586,'613','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The IT business\'s cyclical management activities follow the traditional PDCA management cycle of planning execution, checking, and corrective action: The Planning (P) phase identifies opportunities and issues, sets the and scope for IT business, and establishes an IT business plan for linking business with IT. In the Do (D) phase, the IT business is designed and implemented and the business operations data are collected: In theC (Check) phase, the results of IT business operations are analyzed, the business and IT performance indicators are monitored, and business & IT correlation verification is carried out. In the Action (A) phase, the improvements needed are identified and IT adjustmentslmodifications are made to support the IT business,after which the Planning (P) phase begins all over completing and continuing the cycle of reneat and renewal ad infinitum goals again, The cyclical management structure of IT business is shown in [Fig: 8]. The IT service and IT infra provide operationa support amed at enablinga business (process) toachieve results in its IT business In IT business management, new IT business performance indicators are derived from the service quality of the IT operational support service (IT QoS) and the business performance results of the organization These indicators are then sent to the IT division The IT business management provides support for the making and adjusting of decisions, and investments, to the IT service and IT infra,thus ensuring that the target levels for the performance indicators can be met','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2587,'803','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Before the mid-2000s, IT-related activities or departments were seen as a category of back-office support activties, completely distinct the main activities of a company: However, since the 2000s, when IT companies began to emerge and existing companies accelerated the integration of IT, the perception of the role IT could play and the role of IT-related departments in the value chain model began to change In particular, since 2010, the perception of value chain models from the IT business perspective has changed dramatically, and this change can be seen from two main from','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2588,'803','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','perspectives.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2589,'614','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'68039adcc7f9b.png','/storage/figures/68039adcc7f9b.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2590,'614','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'',NULL,'68039adcde1b1.png','/storage/figures/68039adcde1b1.png','2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:45:16'),(2591,'614','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The value chain model defines the ultimate direction of an enterprise organization in terms of the concept of value The model presents a structure designed to help an enterprise organization realize its value The value chain model has come to be recognized as a critical management theory for analyzing the business activities of an enterprise Furthermore, the value chain model not only provides a very useful framework for aalyzing and understanding a company s competitive advantage from its activties but also introduces the concepts of activities and support activities that have become important reference points for enterprises\' organizational structures key The concept of a business value chain can be approached from two different angles: a traditional manufacturing company ad a e-commerce company From the agle of a traditional manufacturing company a business value chain explains how activities (warehousing, operation [production], shipment, marketing and sales, customer service) and support activities (corporate infrastructure, HR management, technology development, purchasing activities) should be organized and implemented if the company is to reach both its financial and its non-financial objectives. The value chain of an e-commerce company can be used as a tool for increasing business efficiency and effectiveness by electronically handling business processes In this case, the key activities are procurement,, zero-inventory production, third-party logistics, network sales, and online services. The support activities include the deployment of an integrated information platform and network infrastructure, Internet recruitment, and the management of online sunnliers key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2592,'615','App\\Models\\Section','Text','IT is applied throughout all the activities and support activities that constitute the elements of a companys value chain model. This signifies that the role of IT is no longer limited to back-office functions but that IT is integrated and utilized as a key factor in every aspect of a companys activities. For example, let\'s look at the typical example of a hypermarket: Without IT, would it be possible to pursue the five key activities of the value chain model normally or do it ina way that would be competitive? In an environment where managers working for a hypermarket can check inventory ad product information in realtime, place products on shelves in ways that reflect customer shopping behaviors and local characteristics, and collect customers\' purchasing histories in realtime, the answer to this question would be a resounding \'NO\'. In other words, today, when the operations of all key activities defined by the value chain model are based on IT, the above question suggests a new perception about the convergence of the value chain model and IT. Leaving aside the example of hypermarkets, the situation is pretty much the same in other industries referred to as \"smokestack industries\". being key - being key -','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2593,'616','App\\Models\\Section','Text','When a companys business model is e-business or Internet business, it is hard to explain its activities and support activities separately IT For example, Amazoncom is a leading example of a company that performs both its key activities and its supporting activities using IT: Likewise, Interpark in Korea is considered a similar case. In other words, companies that began their operations as IT-based entities cannot be understood if the activities and support activities defined in their value chain models are considered separately: In such situations, the traditional value chain model has to be approached from a new perspective key from key','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2594,'617','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The two perspectives explained above are related to the two angles mentioned when explaining the IT business Just as when one tries to understand the IT business, one must view it in terms of two different trends, that\'s to say one in which IT is integrated into the business processes across the whole company, and another in which IT is used as the main business, the value chain model can also be understood in two different ways. Therefore, since most companies today are pursuing their IT business in the hope of gaining a competitive edge from IT, our understanding of the traditional value chain model must also be expanded from the business perspective Such an expanded understanding of IT is raising several issues in academia and in the field Traditional job processes that have long been taken for granted are driving structural changes in companies following the company-wide integration of IT. Examples include the elimination of unnecessary processes in the decision-making process through the adoption of an intranet information system, and the transformation of a company into a more horizontal organization in which quality information is supplied to all employees information that otherwise would have been held by a privileged few: That is, the perception is spreading that the utilization of IT is not limited to just being integrated into the value chain model activities, but that it is a (new) concept of value chain model that could have & decisive impact on the structure of an entire organization and its competitive advantages','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:35','2025-04-19 12:44:35'),(2595,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Tables',NULL,'',NULL,'68039add02258.png','/storage/tables/68039add02258.png','2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:45:17'),(2596,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Recent Trends and Major Issues','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2597,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Text','The development of a companys IT business strategy is the process of finding the most effective way of achieving its mission and objectives under the constraints of the internal and external environments to which it is subject Setting the right strategy is particularly critical for this new concept of IT business, which involves the integration of IT and business processes. As the domain of IT business continues to expand, and the business process becomes ever more closely integrated with IT, interest is growing in how to establish IT business strategies and find the right way to analyze the environment before setting ones strategies: This section introduces the current model and the future model, which are essential elements in developing IT business strategies as well as the strategies for implementing them, and also presents different methods of analyzing the IT business environment (including SWOT analysis):','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2598,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Learning Objectives','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2599,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Text','1. To be able to explain the IT business strategy 2 To be able to explain the business environment analysis model for formulating IT business strategies','',4,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2600,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Keywords','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2601,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Text','business strategy formulation, IT business environment analysis','',6,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2602,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Header','Preview for practical business','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2603,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Text','In the mid-1990s, Dell Computers of the US. conducted a SWOT analysis with a view to establishing & effective business strategy that would make them highly competitive in the value chain of the computer industry: Dell discovered that its strengths lay in selling directly to customers ad in designing its own computers and components in order to lower its manufacturing costs. It also recognized that its principal weakness was its lack of relationships with local computer dealerships At that time, Dell Computers was faced with threats from rivals such as Compaq ad IBM, both of which enjoyed much stronger brand recognition and an outstanding reputation for quality: The company took note of the fact that customers already had a deep knowledge of computers and knew exactly what wanted in a computer without having to talk to a sales representative: The company sensed an opportunity: It also saw the Internet as a potential marketing tool. The results of Dells SWOT analysis are described below: they','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2604,'55','App\\Models\\Module','Text','After completing the SWOT analysis, DELL incorporated elements of the SWOT findings into its business strategy: The company began assembling ad selling customer-tailored computers after receiving customer orders over the phone,which ultimately resulted in the entire process taking place on the Internet: Dell formulated a strategy that played to its strengths while eliminating its dependence on a local computer network which was its weakest link The threats of better branc recognition ad quality by Compaq and IBM were effectively neutralized by Dells ability to build high-quality computers tailored to each customers individual needs and then assemble and ship them immediately to the customers. posed','',4,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:36','2025-04-19 12:44:36'),(2605,'219','App\\Models\\Lesson','Text','The IT business strategy phase is divided into two parts: establishment of the IT business strategy ad analysis of the IT business environment In the first part, the general concept of establishing a strategy is explained, with the elements that make up a strategy and the process involved in establishing a strategy In the second part, methods of analyzing the external and internal environments are conducted followed by an analysis the consolidated environment that considers the external and internal environments together For the aalysis of the external environment, the PEST technique is employed to analyze the macro-external environment the political,, economic social and technical perspectives An explanation is given of the 5-Force industry structure analysis technique (i.e, analysis of the competitive advantage provided by IT business through 5 factors including the supplier ad buyers negotiating power, level of competition, etc ) which is used to aalyze the micro-exteral environment: This is followed by an explanation of theAP and 3C techniques used in marketing ad competitive market analysis For the analysis of the internal environment,, the McKinsey 7S Method is introduced. This technique uses factors starting with the letter S (shared values, strategy, system, etc ) to analyze the intemal environment the consolidated environment analysis the SWOT analysis technique is explained as a method of simultaneously analyzing the exteral market environment and internal factors SWOT analysis is explained in conjunction with the BCG matrix, which is a technique for selecting a business development strategy by looking at the growth potential and market share of an IT business along from','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2606,'618','App\\Models\\Section','Text','\"Strategy establishment\" is the process of defining strategies for fulfilling an organization s mission. Corporate strategies must incorporate explanations and analyses of the current status of a given company and suggest direction(s) for change The formulated strategies should be directly aligned with the strategies of each unit- level organization The output of strategic planning is a document that describes the top-level strategy and the environments or aims of the organization that could have a impact on the strategy: A strategic plan not only provides the basis for carrying out the specific action steps of the plan, but also provides the overall direction for the enterprise architecture (EA), process improvement, risk management, and portfolio management, and other types of company-wide activities. The subordinate goals and procedures for realizing a companys implementation strategies can be defined si as to reflect issues that are pertinent to each level of the organizations hierarchy: For instance, if the business manager','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2607,'618','App\\Models\\Section','Text','establishes mid-level strategies and based on the corporate strategy, the production staff can then use the mid-level strategies to set their own goal sat their level. goals','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2608,'619','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'<Table3 Elements of a strategy plan',NULL,'68039add1f1b0.png','/storage/tables/68039add1f1b0.png','2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:45:17'),(2609,'619','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Fig 11] The interdependence among the different elements of strategy development',NULL,'68039add3c0a8.png','/storage/figures/68039add3c0a8.png','2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:45:17'),(2610,'619','App\\Models\\Section','Text','There are many different approaches to choose when developing a strategy. At a typical strategy developme stage, the current conditions of the subject company are evaluated, future goals are set, and implementati= strategies for realizing the companys target model are formulated from','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2611,'619','App\\Models\\Section','Text','In a typical strategy development process, the current (As-Is) model of a company is evaluated and a picture of the future (To-Be) model is presented, after which a set of strategies for transforming the company from one model to the other model is developed The interdependence among the different elements of strategy development is shown pclc','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2612,'619','App\\Models\\Section','Text','A companys mission is typically either its objective or its main business A mission describes what an entity does for its own benefit and is not bound by time: A companys vision is the ideal future that it aspires to. A vision can only be obtained by the successful execution of the mission A company\'s vision is both a source of inspiration and an extension of its capabilities als must be measurable high-level, and support an entity in its efforts to achieve its mission ecific, quantifiable and low-level targets which signal that the objectives have been reached Principles state the constraints that a company must consider when selecting the method of achieving its targets. The basic ideology of a company represents its core values, and is used in shaping its strategy: Enablers Enablers are the external environments and corporate strengths that can boost a companys ability to achieve its and objectives. goals Barriers are the external environments and corporate weaknesses that impede an entitys ability to achieve its goals and objectives: Strategy Strategy is the approach a company takes to realize its mission, objectives, and goals. Strategy must support companys vision, but it is affected by enablers, barriers, and the basic ideology: Strategic plan 0 - A strategic plan is a document created through strategic plan setting activities A strategic plan explains the strategy of a company and the factors that affect the strategy: ves are a set of activities carried out to implement a strategy: Actions are specific procedures for achieving _ and objectives: Generally speaking: people are assigned to manage activities, and activities are subject to certain timetable constraints goals','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2613,'619','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The performance index describes the performance target value for each go','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2614,'804','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The purpose of the strategy analysis is to collect the information required to make the business decisions of the company: The internal environment can be improved because it can be controlled by the company, whereas the external environment is generally difficult to control and requires an adaptive strategy: Exleltal eliviOreri alalysis This is an analysis of the environment surrounding a company and other external conditions (Macro-environment) This is the political, economic, social and technological environment surrounding a company: The boundaries of its influence can be expanded across several industries (Micro-environment) As the industrial environment to which a company belongs, the micro-environment is where the company faces competition when acquiring resources and its products/services, and is what we often call general competitive environment selling Internal environment analysis Tilentiai Eiiviiuniietil alialysis The analysis of a companys internal environment focuses on internal elements and processes, resources, organizations, etc, and also focuses on the interal changes taking place within a company: Consolidated environment analysis Cui ibuiualcu Ciiviuiiiciil aniaiysis A comprehensive analysis of the extemal and internal environmental factors of a company is carried out, and integrated interallexternal analysis results can be obtained: SWOT analysis is an important tool of consolidated environment analysis. A SWOT analysis examines the strengths (S) and weaknesses (W) of a companys internal environment and the opportunities (0) and threats (T) present in its external environment','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2615,'805','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','In the strategy selection phase, the best possible direction for the future of the company is selected based on the information collected in the strategy analysis phase If the information obtained the strategy analysis phase is incomplete or defective, it becomes impossible to determine whether the strategy chosen by an organization is the right one Therefore, strategy selection must begin with a thorough review of the results and inferences of the preceding strategy analysis phase during If this process is completed seamlessly, it will produce an optional list of alternatives to a set of strategic directions that a company can adopt It is common for each of these alternatives to have different resource requirements with unique solutions to key issues Each alternative is evaluated according to a reasonably established evaluation standard, and, ultimately, the most appropriate alterative is chosen as the strategic direction','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2616,'806','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','In the strategy implementation and management phase, the chosen strategic alternative is adopted and put into effect: During this phase, several managerial issues could emerge, such as the viability of a companys resources for executing a strategy the readiness of a companys culture and structure, the change management for realizing strategy, the of strategy realization and the development method decision, the strategy implementation readiness of the steering group within the company, and the level of influence over internallexternal stakeholders, etc The progress of the strategy is monitored continuously, and the status of the strategy is delivered from the implementation phase to the analysis phase via a feedback The progress of the strategy may influence the internal or external environment of the company: In addition, the internal or external environment may change due to the occurrence of unexpected events after completion of the strategy analysis Therefore,, a review of the strategy analysis should be conducted to ensure that the chosen strategic direction is still valid path path','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2617,'620','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'12] Strategy setting process [Fig',NULL,'68039add531c2.png','/storage/figures/68039add531c2.png','2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:45:17'),(2618,'620','App\\Models\\Section','Text','The strategy-setting process consists of strategy analysis, strategy selection, strategy implementation and management, and feedback First, in the strategy analysis phase, basic information regarding the company is investigated, and the As-Is model is studied. In the strategy selection phase, the future (To-Be) model and the strategy for realizing the To-Be model are established In the strategy implementation and management phase, the strategy is adopted and put into effect When necessary, adjustments can be made to a strategic plan during this phase.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2619,'220','App\\Models\\Lesson','Text','As the IT business environment is changing and evolving continuously, the targets of an IT business strategy must also be updated continuously if a company is to meet the objectives of its IT business In addition, the of the IT business strategy is to fine-tune the organization and its business to the environment, thereby increasing the likelihood of the organization s survival as well as increasing its chances of achieving its business targets goal','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2620,'807','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 4  PEST analysis and examples of items examined',NULL,'68039add6e2a1.png','/storage/tables/68039add6e2a1.png','2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:45:17'),(2621,'807','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','PEST analysis, technique for analyzing the exteral macro-environment,, is used as a tool for analyzing the impact of political, economic, social, and technological opportunity and threat factors In PEST analysis, brainstorming is carried out to determine the characteristics of the country or region that is the target market for a companys products and business services The table below shows examples of items examined in PEST analysis When legal and environmental factors are included in addition to the four elements of PEST discussed above, PEST is called PESTLE or PESTEL.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2622,'808','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'[Fig.13] Michael Porters 5 Force Analysis',NULL,'68039add84c53.png','/storage/figures/68039add84c53.png','2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:45:17'),(2623,'808','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Porter s Five Forces Framework, a micro-external environmental analysis technique is used to analyze the structure of the industry to which a company belongs It is used mainly in establishing a strategy for securing a competitive edge for a companys products or business services. In this framework, we will analyze the structure of the industry five perspectives: from','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-04-19 12:44:37','2025-04-19 12:44:37'),(2624,'808','App\\Models